A push is when you actively reach out to customers to get them to use your product, while a pull is when customers come to you on their own, often through word of mouth or other organic means.
In the context of Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD), a "push" refers to a situation where a company actively promotes a product or service to potential customers, often through marketing and advertising efforts. The company is essentially trying to "push" the product onto the customer, convincing them that they need it.

On the other hand, a "pull" in JTBD happens when customers actively seek out a product or service because they have a specific job they need to get done, and they believe that the product or service will help them accomplish that job. In this case, the customer's need or desire for a solution "pulls" them towards the product.
